<REFENTRY id="ls">
<REFMETA><REFENTRYTITLE>
ls
</REFENTRYTITLE></REFMETA>
<REFNAMEDIV>
<REFNAME>ls</REFNAME>
<REFPURPOSE>
list directory contents
</REFPURPOSE>
</REFNAMEDIV>
<REFSECT1>
<TITLE>Description</TITLE>
<PARA>
<COMMAND>ls</COMMAND> is as specified in 
<XREF LINKEND=STD.SUSv3>, but with
differences listed below.
</PARA>
</REFSECT1>

<REFSECT1>
<TITLE>Differences</TITLE>
<VARIABLELIST>

<VARLISTENTRY>
<TERM>-p</TERM>
<LISTITEM>
<PARA>
in addition to <XREF LINKEND=STD.SUSv3> behavior of printing a
slash for a directory,
ls -p may display other characters for other file types.
</PARA>
</LISTITEM>
</VARLISTENTRY>

</VARIABLELIST>

<para>
Certain aspects of internationalized filename globbing are optional;
see <xref linkend="localization-glob" />.
</para>
</REFSECT1>

</REFENTRY>
